        <chapter xml:id="week7">
            <title>Week 7 - Optimization</title>
            <section xml:id="section15_3">
                <title>Section 15.3 - Constrained Optimization</title>
                <worksheet>
                    <exercise>
                        <p>
                            <fn>#13 from Section 15.3</fn>Let <m>f(x,y) = x^2+2y^2</m>.
                                <ol type="a">
                                    <li>Compute the critical points of <m>f(x,y)</m>.</li>
                                    <li>Compute the "special points" as identified by the method of Lagrange multipliers subject to the constraint that <m>g(x,y)=x^2+y^2=4</m>.</li>
                                    <li>Find the maximum and minimum values of <m>f(x,y)</m> on the disk <m>x^2+y^2 \leq 4</m>.</li>
                                </ol>
                        </p>
                        <solution>
                            <ol type="a">
                                <li><m>\mathrm{grad}(f) = 2x\vec i + 4y \vec j</m> so the critcal point is at <m>(0,0)</m></li>
                                <li><m>\mathrm{grad}(g) = 2x\vec i + 2y \vec j</m> so we are solving the system of equations
                                    <me> 2x = 2x\lambda \quad \text{and} \quad 4y=2y\lambda</me>
                                    This is a strange one because solving both equations for <m>\lambda</m> yields that <m>\lambda=1</m> and <m>\lambda =2</m>. The one thing we ignored here was the possibilites that <m>x=0</m> or <m>y=0</m>. If <m>x=0</m>, then substituting back into the constraint equation yields <m>0^2+y^2=4</m> which means that <m>y=\pm 2</m>. If <m>y=0</m>, substituting into the constraint equation yields <m>x^2+0^2=4</m> which means that <m>x=\pm 2</m>. Thus, we get 4 important points out of this
                                    <me> (0,-2),(0,2),(2,0),(-2,0) </me></li>
                                <li><p>Plugging the critical point from part (a) and the four points from part (b) yields</p>
                                    <me>f(0,-2)=f(0,2)=8 </me>
                                    <me>f(-2,0)=f(-2,0)=4</me>
                                    <me>f(0,0)=0</me>
                                    <p>Hence, the minimum happens at <m>(0,0)</m> and the maximum happens at <m>(0,-2)</m> and <m>(0,2)</m>.</p></li>
                            </ol>
                        </solution>
                    </exercise>
                </worksheet>
            </section>
        </chapter>
